text: This comment section... here's a summary:  - "Already better than The Force Awakens" Not necessarily. Wait until you watch the movie and then you can give your opinion. Remember when you all said that the TFA trailers were "already better than the prequels"? Saying that something is already better than another thing based only on trailers is for retards (with all due respect).  - "Disney is milking the cow!" Yes, it is, just like LucasFilm has done since 1977 with all kinds of merchandise, novels, comic books, videogames and toys. The difference now is that cinema and TV can be used to tell new stories. How's that a bad thing?  - "Aghh, a female lead once again. Feminist agenda!!" Nope. There's still fewer female core characters than males. Get over it. You're allowed to like female characters.  - "Where are Rey and Finn?" Nowhere. This is a spin-off movie, set weeks or maybe even days before A New Hope. Episode VIII comes next year.  - "Another Death Star?!" Nope. It's the original Death Star. The one from A New Hope.  - "Where are the Bothan spies?". Probably, at their homes. Their thing was with the SECOND Death Star.  And I think that's it. Have a nice day! :)

Yeah I'm sure we'll get those too in the movie, but at the very least it looks like we're going to get more of a variety of action set pieces in a variety of locations that look relatively fresh for Star Wars. Not to mention the effects look believable, yet grand. Sure, it's not a guarantee for the film being perfect, but so far I'm really looking forward to the movie as the characters and plot look like they can keep up with the effective effects.

It looks beautiful, sounds beautiful, but seems shallow and predictable for a 2016 film. text: Darth Vader better be wearing the A New Hope Hope-styled helmet/mask in this movie or else the visual continuity will be ruined. (Minor rant) In each movie, Darth Vader has a different helmet/mask. For example, in A New Hope, the raised ridge that runs from between his eyes to the back of the helmet, travels down much lower in the front. Also, Vader's eyes seem to be caved in so-to-speak due to the fringe of the helmet's tented shape.   In Empire Strikes Back, Vader's eyes are much more visible and the raised ridge that runs between the eyes is a bit higher.  The Return of the Jedi's helmet/mask is a balanced visual mix between the ANH and ESB renditions.   Anyone else recognize the differences of Vader's helmet/mask in each movie? Or is it just me?

text: The Star Wars I remember was "Space Fantasy"; A New Hope was like a fairy tale story (farm boy saves princess and defeats evil with help of an old wise knight, comic relief robots and selfish but good-hearted rogues), Empire Strikes Back brought out the legendary magic (swamp hermit teaches mystic ways of the Force) and classical Greek tragedy (father against son), while Return of the Jedi layed the fantasy on thick with forest dwarves, desert monsters and more.  This movie, however, looks like a generic science fiction war story. There's no magic or a feeling of some deep, mysterious, transcendant lore in it, it just looks like a fanfiction romp.  Nothing wrong with that and I'm sure it will appeal to many, but I'm still waiting for real magic to return to this series.  Force Awakens was okay (its main strength was in its great casting and cinematography), but a solid plot with a unique, timeless, fairy tale fantasy quality to it just wasn't there (that flashback dream sequence at Maz Kanata's Castle was particularly very poor storytelling, Starkiller Base was negligible, and the Force was made to be a gimmicky superpower instead of a wonderful, mysterious magic with transcendent mythological, religious and meditative depth).  Without a solid basis it all becomes transient entertainment, instead of an enduring classic.

Yes, Disney is in it for the money, but they know Star Wars has caliber. They're not hiring just any director and writer, they're putting a lot of effort into this. Force Awakens catered to the nostalgic fans, Rouge One seems to cater to those that always wanted spin-offs revolving on an expanded universe, and I think Ep. text: It's funny seeing all the Lucas bashing.  The man created the characters and the franchise and people still can't their fandom minds away from the prequels.  Well I've always said that if you can do it better then the other person go ahead and do it.  I admire Lucas for sticking to his creative values and not allowing the Hollywood Corporate machine to railroad him into making decisions and movies he did not want to make and for having the business sense to keep the rights he kept that made Lucasfilm into what it became.  How many other movie studios relied on the technology Lucasfilm developed to make their movies enjoyable to watch?  What if Lucas hadn't created the universe he did for everyone to enjoy?  Bash all you want but if it wasn't for his idea to return the Saturday Movie Serial to the modern day big screen none of you would have these movies to enjoy, or bash or talk about nor would the people who made these movies possible have the creative canvas to work and play in.  I don't blame him for "retiring" from Lucasfilm or Star Wars since these days a lot of people have unrealistic expectations from filmmakers and storytellers when it comes to a franchise.  Everyone it seems, when it comes to Star Wars, wants to see carbon copies of the original trilogy so no matter what this franchise does the fan base will never be happy or think any of the films that came after the original three will ever be good enough, there will always be something wrong with how the story is told, how it is written, how it is filmed or the fact that some character that was in a novel, video game or some other Star Wars offshoot wasn't involved or mentioned.  No matter what direction any of the future films takes the fans it seems will never be happy.

text: I think something that tends to be missed is that Star Wars is fundamentally about powerful and iconic imagery. The characters and story are also important, but it's images like X-Wings racing over a lake, the lines of Vader's helmet, or a Star Destroyer passing overhead that are really at the core of what Star Wars is. And I think one of the key reasons why people are excited about this trailer (or any Star Wars trailer) is that it provides us with images that fit what we know Star Wars to be, but that push that visual conception in new and exciting ways. So I for one am very excited about this movie, and any future Star Wars movies, so long as they stay committed to providing us with imagery that blows our minds.
author: John Eiford

text: Hey guys! I'll be your Star Wars tour guide. First off no Rey and Finn aren't in this they will be in Episode 8 next year. This movie has no ties to TFA. Darth Vader is indeed alive and well because this movie is a prequel to the OT (yes that does mean Original Trilogy) that takes place right before A New Hope! This is how they obtain the plans from the first Death Star that leads to Leia receiving at the beginning moments of ANH. Oh and yes this is not the second Death Star, nor the fourth, not the tenth. This is how and where it all began. In ANH, Darth Vader said himself, "There will be no one to stop us this time." Well this is about their story, Rogue One. Save the Rebellion! Save the Dream! A Rebellion against the Empire.

Much like a real father, his mission is to get rid of this evil and protect us from harm. With the aid of our spy droids we will find and capture the rebels and bring them to justice. text: I really love the dark and gritty tone that this trailer is giving off. It seems like this movie is going to revisit some of the locations and characters of the Original Trilogy but from a completely different, and darker perspective. That's why I'm really excited for this movie. The opening scene of Episode VII where the storm-troopers are flying into battle felt very intense, and then the part where Finn gets blood smeared on his helmet from the dying hand of a fellow storm trooper really pushed that dark tone. But then the rest of the movie that vibe was lost and replaced with ... something else, something a bit more toned down. I think that's why Rogue One *could* be better than VII. I also really loved episode III which did a good job of pulling of a more mature, girtty tone and was the best of the prequels IMO.

text: I'm cautiously optimistic about the movie. The idea looks great. Hopefully this won't be another case of the trailer being better than the movie. For me that will be highly dependent on the film's protagonist and her teammates.   I don't mind female leads (quite the opposite, actually). I just want them to be allowed to fail at some point. To actually struggle. To not resemble an RPG character whose stats are maxed out in all categories. Rey sort of fell into that trap. She's a good mechanic (why? she was scavenging parts, not putting things together), a good pilot (when has she ever been in a cockpit of any kind where she can actually see the effects of the buttons she is pressing?), a skilled martial artist (how did she learn this when she was established as a dedicated loner?), a decent marksman (a bit odd, since she said she's never used a blaster in her life before nailing a stormtrooper at a fair distance), an adept Force wielder (she uses the Jedi Mind Trick without ever even seeing of it being done before), and a decent fighter with a lightsaber (wouldn't be so bad if it weren't that lightsabers are more like fighting with flashlights than anything Rey has ever used before). None of these in isolation is a bad thing. Many could have easily been fixed with a single line of dialogue per issue in explanation. Taken altogether, it makes her somewhat uninteresting in that she seems to have no hurdle to overcome the way Luke had to. Maybe if they make her more arrogant in the next film that would help since it would fit nothing appearing to be a challenge.   Oddly, enough what nearly killed Episode VII for me was Kylo Ren. He just wasn't all that threatening. He had all of Anakin's worst traits (and Luke's if you want to exaggerate how he acts when we first met him to insane levels) while lacking Vader's intimidating presence. Really, he should have left that mask on; it was the only thing he had going for him.   This new film might be good. I hope so. If they give all the characters strengths and weaknesses the way they did the crew of the Ghost in Star Wars: Rebels or the crew of the Ebon Hawk from Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic the film will be great. To borrow KOTOR's RPG mechanics as an analogy,  while the lead (the player character) could be quite overpowered by the end of game, there were still things that other characters were better suited for. Everyone had their own specialization (this could be easily magnified or decreased by the player if desired). It also helped the story that the supporting characters were interesting (more so than the lead in many cases) and the villain was at least somewhat intimidating.  With Vader in the mix Rogue One at least has one truly intimidating villain. Hopefully the Rogue One team will be as interesting as the teams I previously mentioned. Nothing is worse than watching a movie where you don't really care what happens to the protagonists.

text: StarWars Movie & TV show timeline:  StarWars episode 1 The Phantom Meance  StarWars episode 2 Attack of the Clones  StarWars The Clone Wars season 1-6 (TV Show)  StarWars Episode 3 Revenge of the Sith  StarWars Episode 3.5 Rogue One   StarWars Rebels season 1-3 so far             (Tv Show)  StarWars Episode 4 A New Hope  StarWars Episode 5 Empire Strikes Back   StarWars Episode 6 Return of the Jedi  StarWars Episode 7 The Force Awakens  StarWars Episode 8 (Being filmed)  StarWars Episode 9 (Unreleased)  For goodness sakes people. You literally have the whole of the Internet at your finger tips. Yet you start asking silly questions in the YouTube comments. When you're seconds away from receiving an answer if you just do some online research... Seriously It's not hard and only takes a few mere seconds.  Disney is in talk about more upcoming StarWars films, they are:   This movie has been confirmed to happen, and will be released on  May 25 2018: Han Solo Anthology  Christopher Miller and Phil lord are directing this film. (Han Solo when he was younger. All the journeys that's he done. How he met Chewbacca, Lando and the Millennium Falcon). The actor who will be playing Han Solos younger self is someone called: 'Alden Ehrenreich'. Look up videos of him to see if you think he can play a good Han Solo.   There's also going to be another Anthology film most likely based around Boba Fett, released in 2020  Boba Fett Anthology  (This will either show Boba Fett when he was slightly younger and he became a Bounty Hunter. Or it will show how he escapes the Sarlacc Pitt and what he decides to do).  My personal opinion: Right I'm 16 and to be honest, please don't get angry at me. StarWars the Force Awakens was a let down for me. Personally I was hyped for it and so was my family, but when watching it there were a lot of let downs for me. When leaving the cinema it just felt empty. For me because there were quite a lot of flaws. Don't get me wrong every movie has its flaws. Yet this movie had  many and a lot of scenes that just didn't make sense. One of the biggest issues was having StarKiller base. I believe they should've saved the third death till episode 9. At the end of episode 9 they could've had a huge battle uniting the heroes against the Sith on Starkiller base, etc:  (just a rough idea) For me I was just disappointed. They had 37 years to come up with an amazing storyline after A New Hope, and instead they released The Force Awakens. Don't get me wrong there was a few good scenes, and if you enjoy it then I don't hate you and I respect your decision. Personally I didn't like it. On the other hand Rogue One looks amazing. It's a StarWars movie that looks to be like no other. We are actually witnessing a huge Sci Fi war driven movie. With apparent scenes like Vader being surrounded by 100s of Rebel troops and then he force smashes the ground around him lifting the troops in the air and then wreaking havoc against them all. Tearing them apart piece by piece. If that is true then Rogue One will be an amazing movie I have no doubts. Regardless even if we don't get that scene in sure there will be other scenes which will be a lot better.

That's what is important. Disney has been churning out quality products, and this looks amazing. Also, did people complain about Harry Potter or Obi Wan or Han Solo being too perfect? text: The amount of people who think this is Episode VIII is maddening. Is it not totally obvious that it isn't? As below: 1. No characters are shown at all that were in The Force Awakens. 2. Shows the Death Star (that strangely enough looks just like the first one). 3. Shows Darth Vader. 4. Shows stormtroopers. 5. Talks about the Rebellion (as in that Rebellion from the original trilogy who fight the Empire). 6. There isn't a "Episode VIII" in the film title. To clear up, the film is set shortly before Episode IV, and shows how a group of rebel spies stole the plans for the first Death Star (which as per Episode IV, are sent to Princess Leia on the Tantive IV to put into R2-D2 and send to Obi-Wan). Everyone clear now?

text: *Yawn* Don't get me wrong, star wars is my favorite movie series/franchise ever. But I honestly couldn't care less for this spin-off. I seriously doubt this movie is going to build anything new to the star wars canon. I don't really see it introducing anything new at all. All I see this movie doing is giving a hefty dose of nostalgia. I wish they'd put more focus to building upon the new story and giving us more to look towards and learn on that instead of beating on the original trilogy. We already know that the rebels went out to steal the death star plans, all this does is give more emphasis. I understand there are people out there who will love this movie, by all means more power to them. I just don't see any reasoning for this movie. I wish this time was being used more for building on the new trilogy and giving us more on the new characters, places, etc.

text: I don't buy the whole the daughter of the death star designer is able to infiltrate the main Empire stronghold where the plans are kept without being noticed even though the "director of advanced research" personally forced her father to work for him.   This especially seems corny when this person is being made out to be somebody who likes to do things in person versus his agents or forces.   He personally takes in Jyn's dad.  He is personally on the battlefield, yet his troops?   Well he has those dudes in black so I guess that is supposed to replace all the many thousands of folks who someone in his position should have under him.  Sure there will be some contrived plot about how she grew up and the empire didn't notice it was her even when she was imprisoned.   But somehow the resistance knows her backstory and the Empire doesn't?  Bad bad bad.   Sure the trailer looks good and so did TFA but plot and story wise it really is overly convoluted and contrived.    Trying to fit family relationships into every single major story line in Star Wars doesn't make sense just because it is star wars.  If anything such a film should be showing how the rebel alliance would have been putting all their forces on this mission with their most crack troops leading the charge, AKA their "special forces".   Because it is an all or nothing gambit.  This movie would be a perfect example to show the state of the rebellion and the cat and mouse game versus the empire.  Yet they are making it seem that they have to scrounge up some folks for their 'special abilities' outside whatever forces the rebels should already have in place to do such a mission (ground forces wise). Obviously we know the Rebels have space fighters.

text: What Gareth and the team at Lucasfilm and ILM did with this movie, well at least this trailer, is sit everything in reality. Even more so that Episode 7. THANK YOU so much for that! Every trailer so far, everything felt real and tangible. For the first time in years there are full of shots where I can't tell if a shot is CGI or models or whatever. I haven't felt that since the 80's. Thank you so much for that! It means so much to the fans.   And for the record, I'm not anti CGI... I don't care what the artists use to make their movie. What I want is to be transported in a world in which I believe and truly immerse into it. Thank you again for finally getting me back in this world I love. Feels so good.

text: I hope the movie puts more into how the rebellion became a cohesive fighting force based around a core ideology not simply a bunch of mercenaries that don't seem too convinced about what they are doing. Yes this is a war movie but normally wars are fought with two sides featuring mostly folks who believe in what they are fighting for. Or in the case of good vs evil, the good guys believe in the cause of good and the bad guys... the not so good. So if this is one of the most pivotal chapters in the rebels war against the empire you would expect more dedicated professional military loyalists at all levels as opposed to such a large number of "rag tag" mercenaries who may or may not be dedicated. Sure mercs have their place but their loyalty is to the money and adventure .... AKA Han Solo. Most war movies are about politics, strategy, logistics and deception which are just as important as the actual fight itself. And in real life you would expect a hardcore group who have been through previous battles leading way not some folks who have to be convinced in some way or another in the rebel cause.

text: What I really want from this movie is a feeling of Jedi absence. Let me explain. I want it to feel sort of like "God is dead. We're truly on our own". That's really a feeling I never got from the original trilogy.  I want it to feel sort of depressing. Like "The Jedi are dead... We have no hope..."   The Jedi were such a monumental factor in the galaxy, that I think the feeling of their being gone is something that needs to be explored.  Or maybe even the idea that no one in the galaxy knows what really went down. After all, the Emperor told everyone that the Jedi were planning a coup of the government. What if most people believed that, but there were some people who said "No that doesn't make sense..." and they were silenced?   I'm really hyped to see the Empire back in play, is what I'm getting at

text: As much as I'm looking forward to this movie, I think this spin off has been badly timed. We just had Episode VII who's story centred around destroying Starkiller Base, put plainly - an upgraded Death Star! Now we have Rogue One... yet another story centred around destroying or at least, finding a way to destroy a Death Star.  That means of the 8 Star Wars films we've had once this is released, 4 of them (50%) had a plot centred around destroying an Imperial Base that can destroy planets. Seriously?  So Lucasfilm (Disney) listen up.... no more Death Stars or Starkiller base plots OK? It's wearing thin and its about time we had a plot that gave us something original, gritty and completely unexpected to get us fans excited. Take the hint!

text: The construction of a moon size weapon that can instantly destroy planets  ' IS ' the ultimate weapon,  but they didn't  develope the concept in depth. The Death Stars in episodes 4 and 6 were just a plot device to give reason for the main characters uniting , and staying united after finding a frozen Han Solo. They seriously  undervalued the Death Star concept . Maybe it was undervalued because they wasn't expecting the story to go beyond the first 3 movies.      Now that the Stars wars stories are expanding then what man made weapon can possibly  top the threat of a planet killer. A galaxy killer ? No, too much power. They started out too high in the threat category with no where else to go , except for a galaxy invasion. This is why in the Force Awakens movie they just recycled the same old threat of a weapon endangering entire  planets.   I rather for them to make movies that focuses mainly on the confrontations between Jedi and Sith. forget about trying to include non force wielders as main characters and just  go balls deep into the force.

text: Just got back from an early screening of the movie, and it's a solid entry into the franchise...speaking for myself, better than the brainfart that was Jar Jar Abrams's "The Farce Awakens"...aka "Copy-And-Paste A New Hope". It has its flaws most definitely...and weirdly enough it is in those moments and scenes when they once again cater too much to fans and the wisps of nostalgia rear their ugly heads. And another noticeable flaw was Michael Giancchino...who is just a safe, unremarkable and bland composer...basically a musical "yes man"...the loss of Alexandre Desplat from the soundtrack was a sizeable blunder. But all in all "Rogue One A Star Wars Story" is a good movie that needs multiple viewings too get all the stuff in it and get the finer points! Two thumbs up for Felicity Jones and Alan Tudyk!______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________PS. Dec.26/'16-- Having seen the movie multiple times now...I can honestly say I love it...a lot...and I've even softened my opinion on the soundtrack and Michael Giancchino. "Rogue One" is the movie I wanted to see for many, many years! Outstanding! Great work by Gareth Edwards, cast and crew!

text: I understand, but some were left with a cliffhanger at the end of Force Awakens. That movie took place after Return of the Jedi. So, Luke is in hiding, Leia is old, and Hans is murdered by his son. Some fans were just wondering what happens next; is peace going to be restored? Instead, we were taking way back to this setting which is basically the uprising to the Galatic Empire. They might be thinking, "How redundant can this be? We know what is going to happen!" Well, would you have been wondering all of this time how this all began? Thus, Phantom Menace, Attack of the Clones, and Revenge of the Sith were produced. So, tie those in to New Hope, Empire Strikes Back and Return of the Jedi to make sense of it.  We can only hope that LucasFilm continues after Luke Skywalker is found to see if the wars FINALLY end. Next December might tell us.

Those were the flaws, but the one thing that isn't really a flaw but still broke my heart is... the ending. I won't say anything more, those who watched it will know. text: I got to say, Rogue One was surprisingly good. Initially, I thought the movie was going to flop in the first 30 minutes of the film. Then in the middle, I felt as if the movie salvaged itself. Then Darth Vader and Grand Moff Tarkin (Peter Cushing resurrection), as limited as their appearances were in the film. Made the movie better. And the final scene with Vader and Princess Leia with the segue to Episode 4  made it more like the traditional Lucas Star Wars films. Minus the opening crawl. I reminisced and  almost got all nostalgic when I saw the two legged AT-ST Imperial Walkers, 4 legged AT AT Imperial Walkers, the Imperial probe droids that we saw in Episode 5 in the Hoth System, the advanced X1 quad drey smaller imperial tie fighters, X wing fighters, and the larger TIE avenger ad TIE defender fighters.
author: Paul Page

text: Rogue One felt more like a traditional Lucas Star Wars film than Episode 7 did. Episode 7 was still good in it's own unique way. But I just felt like The Force Awakens didn't have that trilogy feeling as Episodes 2 thru 6 had. Even the opening crawl in Episode 7 sounded a bit different. text: I loved this movie, it oddly is similar to my favorite game, Halo: Reach. SPOILERS. They both had a darker tone. They were both prequels to the original trilogies.  They both had a majority of the main characters killed (Everyone in Noble Team except Jun and literally everyone in Rogue One). They both had a similar objective of retrieving and transporting important cargo (Cortana and Star Dust). They both lost the fight to the enemy, but not the war. They're both vital to the timelime in Halo/Starwars respectively. They both had main characters from the original trilogy  (Halo: Reach had the Master Chief, Cpt. Keyes, Cortana, and Dr. Halsey while Starwars had Darth Vader, C3PO, R2D2, Princess Leia, and etc).  They both ended it off with where it all began. (With Princess Leia running from  Darth Vader and the Pillar of Autumn runnimg from the Covenant which could as well be another similarity).

text: In my eyes, Rogue One was very much better than Ep. VII. I cannot understand people complaining about that there are no new ideas. Hey, this is a sequel of Ep. III and a prequel to Ep. IV and tells the story, how the Death Star plans got stolen; how much can there be a new story line???   I think, it was worth to make a movie about that chapter of Star Wars history.  But of course I would not reject something different, let's say, some movies about the very old times in Star Wars history, i.e. about the Old Republic and the Sith-Wars. That would be refreshing and a chapter also worth making movies about it, since so far only video games were released featuring the events of the early Star Wars universe.  And actually, I was very surprised that they could recreate the faces of Tarkin and Leia so well! Only Tarkin sometimes looked different than the original actor, but I think, in 5 years from now on, every actor (including his/her voice) who passed away long ago can be "resurrected" for movies.

text: I see a lot of glowing reviews, perhaps I watched a different movie.  The good: For the hard-core fans, yes see it. Also, the story was not a simple remake; that part is good. And, as always, the special effects were great.   The bad: For me, this movie was dark, brooding, had non-stop tiresome violence and killing, was overly long, and had milk toast tie-ins to the characters we know. Also, the audience was assaulted with a plethora of unknown characters without background, context or hope. What was missing: any on-screen friendships that you could care about, light moments, or really anything to make you smile. What little humor/friendship there was, was flatly negated by the end of the movie.  The flick had a very impersonal torch to bear. Like an explosion, the movie tore through the story line in a rush to fill in the gaps of the SW master story line, but in the process, it abandoned any concern for simple warmth, basic charm, or even subtle charisma. I left the theater tired and in a funk; longing for some of the Lucas' bad prequels.   Conclusion: In the end, I don't regret that I saw it, but I would not watch it again; this is one of my least favorite SW films (episode 3 is still at the bottom, by a good margin). Perhaps your take will be better than mine.

text: I prefer not knowing what happens before A New Hope.  Sometimes less is more.  Vader and the Empire storming the ship, and you don't really know what happened before... that's better to me.  Now we have this overly serious movie that doesn't mesh at all with the on purpose mildly campy, swashbuckling, Saturday morning serial feel of the original trilogy.    They call it Star Wars, and it has some of the same Star Wars vehicles, but it doesn't "feel" like Star Wars at all.  It feels like every other modern movie -- completely forgettable.  None of the characters have memorable lines or charm.  It's just expensive looking.
author: kingv911

text: With great anticipation I went to see this movie..  but to my dismay,  this particular episode failed to meet my expectations, with respect to character development and the quality of story telling as exemplified in past episodes.. I use the term "episode" because it felt like the movie was made for TV, rather than being created for the big screen..  The special effects artists were the real stars of the show. The visual artistry shined bright, while the script and story telling aspects of this episode seemed to fail in comparison...  I won't critique the actors performances because, often, great acting can be ruined by bad scripts and bad editing decisions.. I blame the producers....  Star Wars movies, in the past, have been the hallmark of science fiction story telling in the movies.. Lately, Star Wars seems to be lacking in that department... Big budgets don't always equate to good story telling... I believe this episode of Star Wars "died on the cutting room floor.."

text: It is a testament to those who worked on the various designs for Star Wars that they still hold up and look just as good and futuristic as they did almost 40 years ago. When you think about other science fiction series or movies, inevitably ship designs, armour designs have to be updated and redesigned for contemporary reincarnations. But in this movie it looks like they haven't had to do anything to any of the designs, and they still look brilliant, especially with modern effects. X-wings, storm trooper kit, star destroyers, the death star, all still look fantastic in modern hi-def.

text: This movie [Rogue One] is designed to be a mediator between Revenge of The Sith [III] and A New Hope [IV]. The film has to be [in my opinion] the best movie of the entire Star Wars trilogy, including The Phantom of Menace [I], Attack of The Clones [II], Star Wars: Clone Wars [TV Series (three seasons)], Star Wars: The Clone Wars [Movie], Star Wars: The Clone Wars Republic Heroes [TV Series (spanning six seasons)], Revenge of The Sith [III], A New Hope [IV], Star Wars Rebels [TV Series (currently in third season)], The Empire Strikes Back [V], Caravan of Courage: an Ewok Adventure [Movie], Ewoks: The Battle of Endor [Movie], Return of The Jedi [VI], and The Force Awakens [VII]. My opinion may in fact be up for debate considering that I was not alive until the disappointing prequels, The Phantom of Menace and Attack of The Clones, were made. However, Revenge of The Sith [III] does make it to one of my personal favorites despite the opinions of its condescending critics. But without further ado and additions to my argument, I will drive to the point of my comment and say one must go see this movie because it represents the series as a whole in a fantastic manner.

text: this movie is OK - first act: overly staid and dark, second act: overwritten, third act: popcorn fluff.   The writers and director missed the tone of the series, and the 'tough, in the moment' look of all the hand-held cam and shallow depth of focus made the film read like a Borne spy flick. Worse still, they accelerated all the action ala Star Trek Into Darkness so even the vastest, most intricate CGI scenes seem to just buzz by in seconds, making the whole project feel disposable,  Ultimately, you need a good writer with the appropriate tone for the Star Wars mythology, this film feels overwhelmingly like a Gareth Edwards action flick bolted onto Star Wars set pieces, and Gareth Edwards isn't the worlds finest storyteller by any stretch. The PROBLEM with so many group cast FX heavy action/escapism films these days is that the aesthetic is so disposable. Why can't they try and match PACING to naturalistic pacing? Is animation something that editors all speed up 30% in final edit for effect? You can speed up footage to a choppy pace on your home computer . . . these people should stop aping Nolan's choppy Dark Knight picture and look more at the nature of exploring images instead of OD'ing on "choppiness-power" . . .

text: It's been a month and a half since I saw this movie for the first time. I remember at 2:30 am on the Sunday morning after the premiere I woke up to my phone blowing up. I checked my phone and everyone was saying that the movie was incredible. Every second of hype for this film ended up being worth it. No matter what happens in the future, no matter if future episodes are good or bad, I now have another great film that I don't think I'll ever put away. The last fifteen minutes alone would be worth the price of a DVD. I was in tears as soon as the credits started, and I don't cry about anything, especially not films. Thanks to everyone involved in this masterpiece. If superfans like Gareth keep directing, we'll be just fine. That being said, I expect to see A TON of deleted scenes on the blu-ray release. And hopefully even a full 4-hour (or longer) cut. Because we know of at least 2 more Vader scenes, and with the reshoots, there should be about 6 total hours of footage filmed for this movie. I don't care if they have to charge a hundred dollars. I'd buy it.

text: I'm not looking forward to The Last Jedi. The Force Awakens was an overhyped and by-the-numbers cash grab, Rogue One was boring filler that adds nothing of value to the series, and getting one of these movies every year is just setting the franchise up for becoming even more bloated and oversaturated. Why not put some actual time and effort into the story and characters, and create a product that's worth the wait?  I get that they have a brand and it's all about that bottom line. But does Disney REALLY need the merchandising profits that badly? Star Wars was already hugely popular before it was being shoved in your face everywhere you go around the month of December. Four movies that Disney put out last year were among the top five highest-grossing movies of 2016. The other one in the top five? Their own movie, Rogue One. You're not losing any money if you take your time, Disney. It's the basic principle of quality over quantity, I get it, a huge chunk of Disney's consumer base is impatient children who need instant gratification. Kids are demanding little hellions.  Star Wars is becoming more and more of a soulless shell of its former self. They'll be making these movies long after we're dead, until every little thing about the franchise is as familiar and recognizable as the back of your own hand. And they will continue to make money and sell merchandise, and the franchise will reign dominant - not by telling a story or captivating audiences but by pushing a popular and beloved brand.

text: Before I speak my mind, I want to make it clear that I'm 31 years old. So yes, I'm an OT baby and I'd watched each movie five MILLION times before the NT, TFA, Rogue One, and Episode 8 came along...  For the love of GOD! Did you people REALLY think "Rogue One" was going to introduce anything that would go into hiding for 35-40 years...only THEN to "conveniently" reemerge now!? This movie was, in my opinion, the best in the saga to date. It was the PERFECT blend of OT character development and storytelling with NT action sequences and suspense. It FINALLY answered questions (i.e. the opening scroll text of "A New Hope" mentioned the rebellion's first victory...why didn't the movie didn't SHOW the battle and the spies stealing the plans), and it added new details to "A New Hope" that finally helped a lot of things make sense. Like how the Death Star was INTENTIONALLY built by a GOOD guy, so that it could PURPOSEFULLY have an exploitable "weakness". Why would an EVIL engineer build the station and LEAVE the weakness open to chance?

text: One of my favorite moments in all of cinematic history was seeing the Death Star over Jedha, upside down from how we'd always seen it before.  In that moment I knew two things.  One: this movie is serious about the Death Star.  They're actually treating it like an enormous battlestation planet killer.  Two: This planet that we've been on, that Jyn and Cassian have been fighting for, that the Rebels are stationed on, is doomed. Destroying a planet we actually care about for the first time in Star wars...  That's why this movie is safely my favorite film ever.

text: If you remove the words "Star Wars" from the title, Rogue One is a pretty below-average space action movie. The story muddles along without doing anything, the characters aren't developed, the direction is all over the map, scenes felt staged and not organic to the plot, it didn't feel like a living world, there is no furtherance of the franchise lore. .. Come to think of it, you can apply those statements to Disney Star Wars in general. Although I didn't see The Last Jedi.. I had no desire for more, after 2 boring movies that did nothing with themselves.  Once you remove the nostalgia glasses, there is nothing here to appreciate. Disney is content to freeze the franchise in carbonite and simply tote it out for display every year, until people catch on to the fact that it's not actually alive.  As a very basic example of Disney's total lack of creativity: Why are the Imperials using AT-AT Walkers on a sandy beach island planet/area (1:39)? It makes ZERO sense, except that people recognize the image as associated with Star Wars. Why not some hover-boat weapons platform? Why not an agile flying combat craft? They could have done something INTERESTING! But no..we get the same thing that we've seen before, and will continue to see until the profits start to drop.  Say what you will about Lucas, but the man did not repeat himself. Each movie had something Brand New to offer. We miss you, George!
